data.content:
Then register it in `Program.cs`:

```csharp
// Program.cs

var builder = WebApplication.CreateBuilder(args);

// Add Problem Details support + your custom handler
builder.Services.AddProblemDetails();
builder.Services.AddExceptionHandler<GlobalExceptionHandler>();

var app = builder.Build();

// Must come before any endpoint mapping
app.UseExceptionHandler();

app.MapGet("/example/{id}", (int id) =>
{
    // Exceptions thrown here are caught globally — no try-catch needed
    throw new KeyNotFoundException($"Item {id} not found");
});

app.Run();
```

**How it works:**

1. `AddExceptionHandler<T>()` registers your `IExceptionHandler` (.NET 8+).
2. `UseExceptionHandler()` middleware catches all unhandled exceptions and delegates to your handler.
3. The switch expression maps exception types → HTTP status codes.
4. For 500s, the real exception message is suppressed — only a generic detail is returned.

**Example 404 response:**

```json
{
  "status": 404,
  "title": "Not Found",
  "detail": "Item 42 not found",
  "instance": "/example/42"
}
```

This gives you a single place to manage all error-to-response mapping with no per-endpoint boilerplate.
